Ibrahim Isa Pantami, Minister of Communications and Digital Economy has directed the immediate suspension of staff members of the National Identity Management Commission (NIMC accused of involvement in alleged extortion of applicants at the NIMC Bauchi and Kaduna State offices. The directive followed outrage by members of the public over extortion by personnel of NIMC, particularly at some enrolment centers in Bauchi and Kaduna who are cashing in on the rush for NIN by the public to perpetuate fraudulent activities. The Federal Government in a recent policy shift directed that mobile network subscribers would now require the National Identification Number to to update and validate their SIM registration if they must remain on the networks . ABUJA DOCTOR REVEALS HOW MOST NIGERIA MEN ARE NOW OVERCOMING TERRIBLE BEDROOM PERFORMANCE DUE TO THIS BRILLIANT DISCOVERY. DON'T BE A VICTIM! The has prompted nationwide rush amid the COVID 19 pandemic, as subscribers scramble to obtain the NIN. The Minister said the activities of the suspected NIMC staff undermines the directive of government. A statement by NIMC stressed the minister’s zero tolerance for corruption in the enrollment process. Train Accident Kills 3 In Central Tanzania Manchester City Defender Tests Positive For COVID-19 “The Honourable Minister restated his zero tolerance stance on extortion, bribery and corruption and further noted that such unethical practices if allowed to fester and not nip in the bud by taking stiffer actions against the culprits, has the potency of derailing the SIM-NIN Integration project. “Enrolment for the National Identification Number (NIN) is free of charge, and on no occasion should anyone pay to obtain an enrolment form or to have their biometrics captured. “All personnel involved in the enrolment and NIN issuance exercise must carry out their respective duties professionally, fairly and with integrity. “In light of the above, we wish to call on the general public to assist us in p